</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Patients with chronic liver disease exhibit various cardiovascular and pulmonary complications. Hepatopulmonary syndrome results in dyspnea due to intrapulmonary arteriovenous shunting and ventilation-perfusion mismatch. Portopulmonary hypertension occurs in patients with portal hypertension. Intrathoracic portosystemic collateral vascular pathways develop in patients with portal hypertension to allow decompression of the portal vein into the systemic circulation. Hepatic hydrothorax may develop in patients with cirrhosis and ascites. Massive necrosis of the liver from any cause may be associated with acute hypoxic respiratory failure, necessitating ventilatory support. Bacterial infection is common in cirrhotic patients because of a compromised host defense system. Hepatocellular carcinoma may produce hematogenous lung metastases, intrathoracic lymph node metastases, direct intracardiac extension, and pulmonary embolism. Interferon therapy for treatment of chronic active hepatitis C may disturb cellular immune activation in some patients and contribute to the onset and progression of sarcoidosis. Awareness of the various thoracic manifestations in chronic liver disease can be helpful for making a differential diagnosis and planning proper management.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.293085093">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.293085093">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g01x.jpeg" height="1117" width="1476" aria-labelledby="F1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1.</b>  Hepatopulmonary syndrome in a 69-year-old man with liver cirrhosis. High-resolution CT scan (1-mm section thickness) shows dilatation of distal pulmonary arteries with subpleural telangiectasia (arrowheads). (Courtesy of Nestor Müller, MD, PhD, Vancouver Hospital and Health Sciences Center, Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g02a.jpeg" height="1324" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Hepatopulmonary syndrome in a 36-year-old-woman. <b>(a)</b> CT scan (lung window, 7-mm section thickness) shows nodular dilatation of peripheral pulmonary vessels (arrows), which are connected to a feeding artery and draining vein. Also noted is bulging of the azygoesophageal recess (arrowhead), a finding due to dilated paraesophageal veins. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan of the upper abdomen shows liver cirrhosis with splenomegaly and varices. <b>(c)</b> Anterior whole-body image obtained after intravenous injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled macroaggregated albumin shows activity in the brain, liver, and spleen, findings consistent with an intrapulmonary right-to-left shunt.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g02b.jpeg" height="1358" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Hepatopulmonary syndrome in a 36-year-old-woman. <b>(a)</b> CT scan (lung window, 7-mm section thickness) shows nodular dilatation of peripheral pulmonary vessels (arrows), which are connected to a feeding artery and draining vein. Also noted is bulging of the azygoesophageal recess (arrowhead), a finding due to dilated paraesophageal veins. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan of the upper abdomen shows liver cirrhosis with splenomegaly and varices. <b>(c)</b> Anterior whole-body image obtained after intravenous injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled macroaggregated albumin shows activity in the brain, liver, and spleen, findings consistent with an intrapulmonary right-to-left shunt.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g02c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1433" aria-labelledby="F2C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2c.</b>  Hepatopulmonary syndrome in a 36-year-old-woman. <b>(a)</b> CT scan (lung window, 7-mm section thickness) shows nodular dilatation of peripheral pulmonary vessels (arrows), which are connected to a feeding artery and draining vein. Also noted is bulging of the azygoesophageal recess (arrowhead), a finding due to dilated paraesophageal veins. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan of the upper abdomen shows liver cirrhosis with splenomegaly and varices. <b>(c)</b> Anterior whole-body image obtained after intravenous injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc-labeled macroaggregated albumin shows activity in the brain, liver, and spleen, findings consistent with an intrapulmonary right-to-left shunt.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F2C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g03a.jpeg" height="1311" width="1602" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Portopulmonary hypertension in a 57-year-old man with liver cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows cardiomegaly and enlarged pulmonary arteries. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a widened pulmonary trunk with a diameter greater than that of the ascending aorta. <b>(c)</b> CT scan obtained at a lower level shows right ventricular dilatation, bowing of the interventricular septum, and thickening of the free right ventricular wall (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Anterior (left) and posterior (right) images from lung perfusion scanning show multiple patchy defects.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g03b.jpeg" height="1301" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Portopulmonary hypertension in a 57-year-old man with liver cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows cardiomegaly and enlarged pulmonary arteries. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a widened pulmonary trunk with a diameter greater than that of the ascending aorta. <b>(c)</b> CT scan obtained at a lower level shows right ventricular dilatation, bowing of the interventricular septum, and thickening of the free right ventricular wall (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Anterior (left) and posterior (right) images from lung perfusion scanning show multiple patchy defects.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g03c.jpeg" height="1450" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3c.</b>  Portopulmonary hypertension in a 57-year-old man with liver cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows cardiomegaly and enlarged pulmonary arteries. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a widened pulmonary trunk with a diameter greater than that of the ascending aorta. <b>(c)</b> CT scan obtained at a lower level shows right ventricular dilatation, bowing of the interventricular septum, and thickening of the free right ventricular wall (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Anterior (left) and posterior (right) images from lung perfusion scanning show multiple patchy defects.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F3C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g03d.jpeg" height="889" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3d.</b>  Portopulmonary hypertension in a 57-year-old man with liver cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows cardiomegaly and enlarged pulmonary arteries. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a widened pulmonary trunk with a diameter greater than that of the ascending aorta. <b>(c)</b> CT scan obtained at a lower level shows right ventricular dilatation, bowing of the interventricular septum, and thickening of the free right ventricular wall (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Anterior (left) and posterior (right) images from lung perfusion scanning show multiple patchy defects.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F3D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g04x.jpeg" height="1590" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4.</b>  Esophageal varices in a 55-year-old man with liver cirrhosis. Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows esophageal wall thickening and enhanced dilated esophageal veins with intraluminal protrusions (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g05a.jpeg" height="1317" width="1692" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Paraesophageal varices in a 50-year-old man with liver cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows lateral bulging of the left paraspinal interface with obliteration of the descending thoracic aortic interface (arrow). Also noted are fibrotic linear opacities in both upper lung zones with volume loss, an appearance due to old pulmonary tuberculosis. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows dilated paraesophageal veins (arrow). Gynecomastia is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g05b.jpeg" height="1376" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Paraesophageal varices in a 50-year-old man with liver cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows lateral bulging of the left paraspinal interface with obliteration of the descending thoracic aortic interface (arrow). Also noted are fibrotic linear opacities in both upper lung zones with volume loss, an appearance due to old pulmonary tuberculosis. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows dilated paraesophageal veins (arrow). Gynecomastia is also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g06a.jpeg" height="1357" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Cardiophrenic varices in a 63-year-old woman with liver cirrhosis caused by membranous obstruction of the IVC. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows widening of both paraspinal interfaces (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows dilated cardiophrenic veins (arrowhead). Also noted are dilated azygos and hemiazygos veins (arrows) and subcutaneous collateral vessels in the chest wall. <b>(c)</b> Angiogram obtained after contrast material injection through a catheter located in the IVC shows abrupt obstruction of the IVC (arrow) and opacification of multiple collateral veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g06b.jpeg" height="1358" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Cardiophrenic varices in a 63-year-old woman with liver cirrhosis caused by membranous obstruction of the IVC. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows widening of both paraspinal interfaces (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows dilated cardiophrenic veins (arrowhead). Also noted are dilated azygos and hemiazygos veins (arrows) and subcutaneous collateral vessels in the chest wall. <b>(c)</b> Angiogram obtained after contrast material injection through a catheter located in the IVC shows abrupt obstruction of the IVC (arrow) and opacification of multiple collateral veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g06c.jpeg" height="1380" width="1727" aria-labelledby="F6C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6c.</b>  Cardiophrenic varices in a 63-year-old woman with liver cirrhosis caused by membranous obstruction of the IVC. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows widening of both paraspinal interfaces (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows dilated cardiophrenic veins (arrowhead). Also noted are dilated azygos and hemiazygos veins (arrows) and subcutaneous collateral vessels in the chest wall. <b>(c)</b> Angiogram obtained after contrast material injection through a catheter located in the IVC shows abrupt obstruction of the IVC (arrow) and opacification of multiple collateral veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F6C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g07a.jpeg" height="1333" width="1674" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Hepatic hydrothorax in a 60-year-old man with liver cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows a large amount of pleural effusion in the right hemithorax. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan of the upper abdomen shows a focal defect in the right posterior diaphragm (arrow), a finding indicative of a Bochdalek foramen. Also noted are right pleural effusion and ascites.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g07b.jpeg" height="1056" width="1314" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Hepatic hydrothorax in a 60-year-old man with liver cirrhosis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows a large amount of pleural effusion in the right hemithorax. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan of the upper abdomen shows a focal defect in the right posterior diaphragm (arrow), a finding indicative of a Bochdalek foramen. Also noted are right pleural effusion and ascites.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g08a.jpeg" height="1215" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  ARDS in a 49-year-old woman with fulminant hepatitis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows diffuse opacity in both lungs. <b>(b)</b> High-resolution CT scan (1-mm section thickness) shows diffuse ground-glass opacity in both lungs. The patient underwent intubation in the following hours.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g08b.jpeg" height="891" width="1332" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  ARDS in a 49-year-old woman with fulminant hepatitis. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows diffuse opacity in both lungs. <b>(b)</b> High-resolution CT scan (1-mm section thickness) shows diffuse ground-glass opacity in both lungs. The patient underwent intubation in the following hours.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g09a.jpeg" height="1613" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Pneumonia in a 53-year-old man with alcoholic liver disease. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows consolidation in the left lung and poorly defined nodules in the right lung. <b>(b)</b> CT scan (lung window, 5-mm section thickness) shows multiple poorly defined nodules in both lungs and consolidation with a small cavity in the left lower lobe. Sputum culture demonstrated <i>Pseudomonas aeruginosa</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g09b.jpeg" height="1370" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Pneumonia in a 53-year-old man with alcoholic liver disease. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows consolidation in the left lung and poorly defined nodules in the right lung. <b>(b)</b> CT scan (lung window, 5-mm section thickness) shows multiple poorly defined nodules in both lungs and consolidation with a small cavity in the left lower lobe. Sputum culture demonstrated <i>Pseudomonas aeruginosa</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g10a.jpeg" height="1412" width="1584" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Pneumonia with empyema in a 54-year-old man with alcoholic liver disease. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows a fluid collection with an air-fluid level in the right hemithorax. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows the loculated fluid collection in the right pleural space with pleural enhancement. Consolidation is also noted in the right lower lobe. Culture of pleural fluid demonstrated <i>Streptococcus constellatus</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g10b.jpeg" height="1395" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Pneumonia with empyema in a 54-year-old man with alcoholic liver disease. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows a fluid collection with an air-fluid level in the right hemithorax. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows the loculated fluid collection in the right pleural space with pleural enhancement. Consolidation is also noted in the right lower lobe. Culture of pleural fluid demonstrated <i>Streptococcus constellatus</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g11a.jpeg" height="1476" width="1449" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Miliary and bronchogenic pulmonary tuberculosis in a 31-year-old man with alcoholic liver disease. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows innumerable small nodules in both lungs. The blunting of the right costophrenic angle is suggestive of pleural effusion. <b>(b)</b> High- resolution CT scan (1-mm section thickness) shows centrilobular nodules and a tree-in-bud appearance (large arrows) mixed with miliary nodules (small arrows) throughout both lungs. Tiny nodules abutting the fissure (arrowheads) and pleura are also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g11b.jpeg" height="856" width="1242" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Miliary and bronchogenic pulmonary tuberculosis in a 31-year-old man with alcoholic liver disease. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows innumerable small nodules in both lungs. The blunting of the right costophrenic angle is suggestive of pleural effusion. <b>(b)</b> High- resolution CT scan (1-mm section thickness) shows centrilobular nodules and a tree-in-bud appearance (large arrows) mixed with miliary nodules (small arrows) throughout both lungs. Tiny nodules abutting the fissure (arrowheads) and pleura are also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g12a.jpeg" height="1336" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12a.</b>  Hematogenous pulmonary metastases in a 63-year-old man with liver cirrhosis and HCC. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained at the subcarinal level shows multiple nodules in both lungs and right pleural effusion. <b>(b)</b> CT scan of the upper abdomen shows multiple masses of heterogeneous low attenuation in the liver with high-attenuation iodized oil infused for chemoembolization. A mass invading into the IVC is noted (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F12A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g12b.jpeg" height="1203" width="1620" aria-labelledby="F12B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12b.</b>  Hematogenous pulmonary metastases in a 63-year-old man with liver cirrhosis and HCC. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained at the subcarinal level shows multiple nodules in both lungs and right pleural effusion. <b>(b)</b> CT scan of the upper abdomen shows multiple masses of heterogeneous low attenuation in the liver with high-attenuation iodized oil infused for chemoembolization. A mass invading into the IVC is noted (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F12B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g13a.jpeg" height="1183" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13a.</b>  Mediastinal lymph node metastases in a 47-year-old man with liver cirrhosis and HCC. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows enlarged lymph nodes in the right paratracheal area. <b>(b)</b> CT scan of the upper abdomen shows high-attenuation iodized oil in the liver and conglomerated lymph nodes in the porta hepatis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g13b.jpeg" height="1146" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Mediastinal lymph node metastases in a 47-year-old man with liver cirrhosis and HCC. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows enlarged lymph nodes in the right paratracheal area. <b>(b)</b> CT scan of the upper abdomen shows high-attenuation iodized oil in the liver and conglomerated lymph nodes in the porta hepatis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g14a.jpeg" height="1302" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14a.</b>  Tumor extension into the IVC and right atrium with pulmonary tumor emboli in a 43-year-old man with HCC. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan of the main pulmonary arteries shows tumor emboli (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> CT scans of the heart <b>(b)</b> and upper abdomen <b>(c)</b> show a diffuse infiltrative mass of low attenuation in the right hepatic lobe that extends into the IVC (arrow in <b>c</b>) and right atrium (arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F14A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g14b.jpeg" height="1287" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14b.</b>  Tumor extension into the IVC and right atrium with pulmonary tumor emboli in a 43-year-old man with HCC. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan of the main pulmonary arteries shows tumor emboli (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> CT scans of the heart <b>(b)</b> and upper abdomen <b>(c)</b> show a diffuse infiltrative mass of low attenuation in the right hepatic lobe that extends into the IVC (arrow in <b>c</b>) and right atrium (arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F14B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g14c.jpeg" height="1294" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14c.</b>  Tumor extension into the IVC and right atrium with pulmonary tumor emboli in a 43-year-old man with HCC. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan of the main pulmonary arteries shows tumor emboli (arrows). <b>(b, c)</b> CT scans of the heart <b>(b)</b> and upper abdomen <b>(c)</b> show a diffuse infiltrative mass of low attenuation in the right hepatic lobe that extends into the IVC (arrow in <b>c</b>) and right atrium (arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F14C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g15a.jpeg" height="1566" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15a.</b>  Sarcoidosis induced by interferon therapy in a 47-year-old man with chronic hepatitis C virus infection. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows diffuse reticulonodular opacities in both lungs. <b>(b)</b> High-resolution CT scan (1-mm section thickness) shows numerous tiny lung nodules with a perilymphatic distribution and interlobular septal (arrowheads) and peribronchovascular interstitial (arrow) thickening in both lungs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F15A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085093/asset/images/g09ma07g15b.jpeg" height="964" width="1458" aria-labelledby="F15B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15b.</b>  Sarcoidosis induced by interferon therapy in a 47-year-old man with chronic hepatitis C virus infection. <b>(a)</b> Chest radiograph shows diffuse reticulonodular opacities in both lungs. <b>(b)</b> High-resolution CT scan (1-mm section thickness) shows numerous tiny lung nodules with a perilymphatic distribution and interlobular septal (arrowheads) and peribronchovascular interstitial (arrow) thickening in both lungs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085093&amp;id=F15B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Huffmyer</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">JL</span></span>, Nemergut EC. Respiratory dysfunction and pulmonary disease in cirrhosis and other hepatic disorders. <em>Respir Care</em>2007; 52: 1030– 1036.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17650360/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Respir+Care&amp;publication_year=2007&amp;pages=1030&amp;pmid=17650360">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="R2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">King</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">PD</span></span>, Rumbaut R, Sanchez C. Pulmonary manifestations of chronic liver disease. <em>Dig Dis</em>1996; 14: 73–82.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1159/000171540">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a 